SECTION 4 — GUIDE CHANGES: EX.2 (OPEN WEBUI MODEL SETUP AND VERIFICATION)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

4.1 MODEL SELECTION IN OPEN WEBUI

  After creating the wall-e model in Ollama, it is available in Open WebUI
  automatically (Ollama syncs the model list on connection). The guide should
  instruct the user to:

  Option A — Select wall-e:latest as the default model in Open WebUI chat.
  Option B — Create an Open WebUI model entry in Workspace → Models pointing
    to wall-e:latest. This allows per-model system prompt customisation
    through the UI without editing the Modelfile.

  IMPORTANT: If the system prompt is set BOTH in the Modelfile AND in the
  Open WebUI model, the Open WebUI system prompt OVERRIDES the Modelfile
  system prompt. Choose one location. The Modelfile approach (described in
  EX.1 above) is recommended because it is persistent across Open WebUI
  updates and applies to all clients including Home Assistant.

4.2 NATIVE MODE CONFIRMATION

  The guide should add this step after model selection:

  Open WebUI → Workspace → Models → wall-e → (edit) → Advanced Parameters
  → Tool Calling: confirm it is set to "Native" not "Legacy/Default".

  CONCEPT: Native mode means Open WebUI passes tool definitions to the model
  in its native function-calling format and the model emits structured JSON
  tool calls. Legacy mode injects a prompt template instead. Native mode is
  faster, more reliable, and required for Qwen3's tool-calling architecture.

4.3 TOOL REGISTRATION UI: CORRECTED INSTRUCTIONS

  CURRENT GUIDE TEXT (incorrect): implies the function list in the Admin Panel
  will populate after a successful connection.

  CORRECT BEHAVIOUR (confirmed in live testing):
  After clicking Save on a tool server registration, the connection status
  shows "Successful Connection" and the function list below it shows ZERO
  entries. This is the correct and expected state in current Open WebUI
  builds. The schema is fetched and parsed internally — the UI does not
  display parsed functions. Do not treat an empty function list as an error.

  PRIMARY SUCCESS INDICATOR (add to guide):
  Immediately after registering a tool, send a test message in a chat with
  the tool enabled and check:
    docker logs mcpo 2>&1 | grep "Calling endpoint" | tail -5
  A POST entry appearing confirms the tool was invoked. This is the only
  reliable success signal.

4.4 REWRITTEN FUNCTIONAL TESTS

  REMOVE the current EX.2 tests:
    Test 1: "List the files in /nc-data"
    Test 2: "Remember that my test value is 42"
    Test 3: "What is my test value?"
    Test 4: memory persistence across restarts

  REPLACE WITH:

  PREREQUISITE: Enable BOTH filesystem and memory tools in the chat via the
